<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<chapter xml:id="ch-irrational-numbers" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Irrational Numbers</title>

  <introduction>
    
    <p>
      Up to this point, we have primarily worked with <term>rational numbers</term>—numbers 
      that can be expressed as a simple fraction of two integers. However, as the 
      ancient Greeks famously discovered, the number line contains gaps that rational 
      numbers cannot fill.
    </p>
    <p>
      In this chapter, we explore <term>irrational numbers</term>. These are numbers 
      that cannot be written as a fraction <m>\frac{a}{b}</m>, and when expressed as 
      decimals, they continue forever without repeating a pattern. We will learn how 
      to identify these unique values, perform algebraic operations with radicals, 
      and understand why constants like <m>\pi</m> and <m>\sqrt{2}</m> are essential 
      for describing the world around us.
    </p>
 
  </introduction>

